metadata.name: EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS #100
metadata.description:
EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS

after symbol 2525, 
aint gonna need to load, write no code
everything you think, do and say
is in the streams that you watch today (oh oh oh)

We find this code is very much alive. They are epi. They are hyper. They are derp. They are flardioids.

Epihyperderpflardioids is the name I have given to a large family of symmetrical loopy shapes, based on sine waves and rotations, reminiscent of the mathematical toy game "Spirograph", but also different. I studied them extensively, but don't claim to understand them fully, yet. I hope you enjoy them as much as I do.

These 365 Epihyperderpflardioids were generated for FXhash's one year anniversary.

metadata.name: Klyft #327
metadata.description:
‚ÄúKlyft‚Äù is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.

Klyft is a juxtaposition of two different projections for the future. One, made by the World Economic Forum, suggests that the global gender gap will have closed by the year 2154. The other, by the UN IPCC, estimates that global warming will reach 3.2 degrees celcius by the year 2100.

Klyft makes use of the unique temporal aspect of computational art by developing its expression gradually over the next 132 years. As we come closer to 2154, the space between the two shapes in Klyft will grow smaller to symbolize the closing of the gender gap. As time goes on, however, Klyft also becomes more and more glitched out to represent the projected increases in greenhouse gases and climate catastrophes.

In the end, Klyft‚Äôs expression will be heavily corrupted, and the two shapes will have reached each other.

¬∑ URL parameters ¬∑

You can add the following parameters to the URL to change the behavior of the piece.

date=<YYYY-MM-DD> ‚Äî See how Klyft looks on another day. Use the format YYYY-MM-DD. 

color=<number> ‚Äî See the piece in another color scheme. The numbers loop around, so 17 equals 0, 18 equals 1, etc. 

resolution=<number> ‚Äî View the piece in a higher resolution. 1 is normal resolution, 2 is double, etc. No decimals allowed.

image=true ‚Äî Save the piece as an image. 

record=true ‚Äî Save the piece as a video in WEBM format.

Adding the following URL parameters will show Klyft in double resolution on the day gender equality is achieved according to the WEF:

date=2154-01-01&resolution=2

Adding the following URL parameters will save a video of Klyft in the ‚ÄòStokkendahl Dalgas‚Äô color scheme:

color=14&record=true

¬∑ Interactions ¬∑

Pressing the following keys will trigger functionality as well as add related URL parameters automatically. 

Pressing D will increment the date by 1 year.

Pressing C will increment the color index by 1.

Pressing R will toggle between normal and double resolution.

Pressing I will toggle the image URL parameter, which saves the piece as an image. Only works outside of iframe.

Pressing V will toggle the video URL parameter, which saves the piece as a video. Only works outside of iframe.

There are secret key presses as well. Some of them only work outside of iframe. 

¬∑ Accessibility ¬∑

Klyft is built to support screen readers. It has been tested using MacOS‚Äô VoiceOver, and uses p5.js‚Äô describeElement() to provide screen reader functionality.

If you have any comments (good or bad) on the screen reader integration, don‚Äôt hesitate to reach out on my Twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art. 

¬∑ Credits and license ¬∑

Klyft is made with p5.js.

Klyft is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: Parametric Decoy #15
metadata.description:
The project started with the discovery of an unusual shape. Draw two parallel sine arcs and connect their opposite points. That's how you get one slice of Parametric Decoy. The shape may appear in its different phases. Sometimes elegant, sometimes awkward. Sometimes broken, sometimes symmetrical. Only connectivity stays the same.

Features:
- size: small, medium, large
- color: *several options*
- background: transparent, halftone, cutout
- distorted: no, maybe*, twisted, displaced, yes**

* "maybe" means I'm not quite sure if distortion affects visible part of the shape
** "yes" means combination of "twisted" and "displaced"

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Made with p5js, inspired by pop-art collages and my own geometric sketches

metadata.name: Perpendicular Inhabitation #187
metadata.description:
'Perpendicular Inhabitation' is a generative collection exploring the relationship between the urban landscape and the human experience, particularly feelings of nostalgia and more specifically 'anemoia' : the feeling of nostalgia for a time or place that we may not have actually experienced first hand. 

Despite depicting a stylised modern architectural language, at its core the collection serves as a homage to 1980s Japan, an era of unprecedented prosperity that left a lasting impression on the music and artwork of the time. Through the use of carefully created palettes and composition, the outputs intend to evoke feelings of optimism, while guiding viewers to consider why the essence of this era is so alluring in the present day as it continues to influence and inspire contemporary art.

The use of exaggerated perpendicular verticals, as well as the heavily foreshortened mountain ranges present in some outputs, convey a sense of hope and possibility for the future. What does it feel like to hope and dream in the city? To look up and be filled with a sense of wonder from the built environment around you?

This project has been created with print in mind at a ratio of 3:4

It is recommended to examine your outputs at full size in order to enjoy them to the fullest.

You are encouraged to return often to notice things you may not have seen previously.

Generated with code using p5.js

Images are generated at 2400 x 3200 px. 

To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

Depending on the complexity of each output, please wait up to 10 seconds for the image generation to complete.

metadata.name: Natt #97
metadata.description:
Natt is a short exploration of a view. On not so recent travels I captured a photo of a small town across a large body of water. It was night and the photograph was blurry, but the emotion stayed with me. It was an emotion of calm and tranquility, accepting the darkness of night and knowing that across the water was a group of people living together, creating a beacon of light. 

Natt is the generative take on this photograph, attempting to capture the same emotion in a purely digital format. 


Press ‚Äúspace‚Äù to pause the animation and ‚Äús‚Äù to save the current view.

For higher resolutions, add ‚Äú?pd=x‚Äù (x being a number >1) to the url when in live view and refresh, then press ‚Äús‚Äù to save. Note, for higher values of ‚Äúx‚Äù rendering will take longer, start with a low number like 2-3 and work your way up to the desired size. 


Generative artwork by Tengil, 2022.

For licenses see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt.

metadata.name: Sixty# #69
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there‚Äôs room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Dissolve #4
metadata.description:
"Dissolve" is an Animated, painting-like abstract generative artwork.
Started as an exercise to custom shaders and the final idea early became to generate an image that looks like a painting eg. chalk or spatula like look on canvas, however not a static final image as usual but with some animated elements. Like a "live" painting.

From technical point of view, in short: there are 2 main different graphic buffers (2D and 3D) to draw some basic-primitive shapes/objects and the final frame is a mixing (or clear) with some pixel manipulation eg. dissolve - noise and other processing performed inside my custom shader.
The speed of shaders (power of hardware acceleration - GPU) allows the processing of multiple frames per second thus allowing animated "painting" - looking final results.

Enough with the description :)

CONTROLS

KEYS:

1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
S: Save a png file with the current resolution
UP arrow: Increases the animation Speed
DOWN arrow: Decreases the animation Speed
R: Reset speed to default
SPACEBAR: Start/Stop animation

MOUSE:

CLICK: Start/Stop animation

----
Made with p5js and custom shaders

¬© Oct. 2022  @Uniray_net | uniray.net

metadata.name: Emotional Sediments #27
metadata.description:
"Emotional Sediments," embodies an artistic exploration that delves into the intricate layers of human emotions, akin to a cartographic journey into the mind's terrain. Employing a deliberately unrestrictive algorithm, this project breathes life into a canvas with a unique blend of strokes and hues. It's akin to a digital conductor, orchestrating the interplay of abstract elements, ultimately crafting a modified emotional landscape devoid of predetermined routes or definitions.

Technical Artistry

The conceptual framework behind this collection revolves around an algorithm powered by digital nuance, akin to a digital brush. Purposefully devoid of conventional emotional norms, this algorithm weaves patterns and textures reminiscent of emotions but refrains from a direct replication. It resembles the abstract contours of emotional landscapes, much like topographical maps or intricate emotional architectures.

Spectator's Insight

What sets "Emotional Sediments" apart is its implicit invitation to interpretation and reflection. The randomly generated emotional strokes lay the foundation for the viewer's imagination to flourish. This versatile canvas becomes the stage for an array of potential emotional narratives: some may perceive the intricate labyrinth of human emotional complexities, while others may envision the winding paths through the highs and lows of the emotional journey. Some might even picture the intricate connections between the different emotional states, or the borders that define our emotional boundaries. In essence, while the canvas remains neutral, it offers boundless territory for emotional exploration and creative introspection.
